The world born on September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the 9/11 terrorist attacks in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists had taken control of four civilian planes, launched two of the aircraft at the World Trade Center towers in New York, hit the Pentagon with a third, and then led to the crash of a fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another American government building in Washington, DC.
All the air pirates were from the Middle East, and 15 from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of a planned, organized, and led operation by Al-Qaïda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
At the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women, and children were killed, and more than 6,000 were injured.
Most were Americans, although citizens from over a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
At the time, many feared that 9/11 would usher in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaïda followed, including several explosions on Madrid trains in March 2004, and the attack on public transportation in London in July 2005.
Terrorists swearing allegiance to the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and carried out a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to hit pedestrians).
However, neither the United States nor any of its allies have ever suffered an attack of a comparable scale to those of September 11 – which are unparalleled.
It is thus worth asking: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference did September 11 make?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
There are many reasons why the terrorists failed to carry out other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaïda lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments around the world have put in place control procedures making it more difficult for potential terrorists to access airports and aircraft.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the rare areas where states often in disagreement are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is now a wide consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments cannot distinguish between terrorists and those who provide them sanctuary and support.
The time when individuals and groups willing to kill for their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters is over.
It is not to say that terrorism has stopped claiming the lives of several tens of thousands of people every year.
However, almost all attacks take place in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia as part of ongoing conflicts (primarily in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks of the 9/11 type against major powers.
Terrorism is becoming increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaïda, for example, survived the elimination of Ben Laden by US special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the 9/11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no resolution of the problem in sight.
The possibility of another 9/11 cannot be ruled out, although the US government has recently stated that the "most urgent terrorist threat" to the country exists domestically.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army put it after their failed attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today, we did not have luck, but remember that we only need luck once."
You will need it always."
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists will get their hands on nuclear material, or will manage to manufacture and use a biological or chemical weapon, at which point terrorism could determine the course of history.
For now, that is not the case.
The 9/11 attacks, however, marked a historic turning point, with a profound impact on US foreign policy over the past 20 years.
While the attacks did not usher in an era of global terrorism, they did indeed trigger the famous global war on terror, with major consequences for US behavior worldwide, America's image abroad, and how many Americans came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Shortly after the 9/11 attacks, the United States offered the Taliban, who controlled the Afghan government at the time, a choice: hand over the Al-Qaïda leaders who were about to leave the country and were responsible for organizing the 9/11 attacks, or risk their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over the Al-Qaïda leaders, American intelligence and military collaborated with a loosely structured Afghan tribal alliance called the Northern Alliance to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
However, this control was never total or uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaïda sought refuge in neighboring Pakistan, where they gradually regained strength and resumed their military operations against the government that had replaced them.
On the other hand, the United States did not work hard enough to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of a sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, America strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, effectively becoming a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, the US intervention in Afghanistan mobilized more than 100,000 American soldiers.
Over twenty years, the cost of the operations exceeded $2 trillion, resulting in more than 2,300 American lives lost, and several tens of thousands of Afghan lives.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The US presence deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy, and sparked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more persevering than America, which in 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict doomed to end in an indefinite stalemate.
The war on terrorism also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have taken military action if 9/11 had not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to want to show the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had put it during the Vietnam War, a "pitiful, helpless giant."
This led some members of the administration (notably Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of terrorists acquiring weapons of mass destruction, which Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (although this was ultimately not the case, according to most participants).
Others wanted to promote democracy in Iraq, and eventually throughout the Middle East, considering that this approach was not only feasible but would also make the region much less likely to produce terrorists and support them.
The Iraq War, which began in March 2003, did not unfold as the Bush administration and many members of Congress (including Joe Biden, who was a senator at the time) and global leaders had envisioned or predicted.
The United States was not prepared for the majority of the events that followed.
Military victories were initially achieved, which certainly allowed for the removal of the government, but soon gave way to widespread unrest and a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army and exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs exacerbated an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, demonstrated the limitations of what military force can achieve at a reasonable cost and within a reasonable timeframe.
In the end, the United States was forced to strengthen its military presence, to nearly 170,000 soldiers, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability was achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but at a much heavier human toll: more than 4,000 American soldiers killed, a significantly larger number of wounded, and a skyrocketing rate of suicides among American military personnel (both in Iraq and Afghanistan).
This total excludes, however, the deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for which estimates vary widely, but whose number is certainly in the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq also weakened the United States in other ways.
No evidence has ever shown Iraq's involvement in the 9/11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for a military intervention without UN approval – aimed at eliminating Saddam's WMDs – turned out to be based on no real grounds.
The images of American soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners further tarnished the country's reputation.
Furthermore, a war-torn Iraq has become synonymous with an emerging Iran as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if Israel is considered).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States was intensively involved in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted in favor of the United States, both in Europe and East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia, as well as a stronger and more assertive China.
The global war on terror could not provide and did not provide the United States with a compass in its approach to foreign policy in the face of a renewed rivalry between great powers.
The wars fought in the aftermath of 9/11 also had significant internal consequences for the United States.
They shook the confidence in a country that had emerged from the Cold War with an historically unprecedented dominant power, and undermined the national unity that had surfaced in the immediate aftermath of the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars also fueled opposition to a major and lasting global role for the United States, giving birth to a new isolationist trend.
Similarly, this warlike propensity, associated with the 2007-2009 global financial crisis and its economic repercussions, has severely impacted Americans' trust in elites, thus stimulating the rise of a populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to the rise of Donald Trump to power.
Today's America is more divided than ever internally, and less willing to engage in this active form of foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, and which has largely benefited Americans and many others.
In retrospect, we can now consider 9/11 as a harbinger of what was to come: less the globalization of terrorism than the fears of globalization.
The attacks conveyed the message that distance and borders mattered little in the global era.
Nothing remains local for long now, whether it's terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis that originated in poor American financial management.
We are currently all facing a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its appearance in China in December 2019.
The fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that devastate many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, which itself is the cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable amounts of greenhouse gases that trap heat in the atmosphere.
The era marked by recent events brings an end to a cycle, marking the 20th anniversary of the US intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly driven out of power; in recent weeks, they have regained it just as easily.
It is too early to know if the Taliban will return to their old habits by becoming a sanctuary for terrorism once again, and if terrorists around the world will rejoice in their victory over America and its allies.
What we know, however, is that terrorism remains a feature of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that already determines it.
